&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;As you might expect really. I loop over each of the 2^6=64 test cases, 
&gt;apply the inputs adjusted so that true=0.9 and false=0.1, then interpret 
&gt;the output as false for &lt;0.5 and true for &gt;=0.5. 
&gt;
... and the fitness is assigned as the closeness to the expected output, 
1.0 for spot on, 0.0 assigned for completely wrong. Total score is thus 
however many test cases there are (64, 2048 etc). I also add an 
additional large value if the network passed all of the tests so that I 
can see when a solution has been found even if the champ gives outputs 
very close to the threshold - and thus generates a fitness somewhat less 
than the number of tests cases.

Colin.
